{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Typography · Stisla v3{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Typography</h1>
    <p class="lead">Headings, display scale, and the long-form treatment for article content.</p>
    <p>Stisla has two typographic contexts. The pattern classes on this page — <code>.h1</code>–<code>.h6</code>, <code>.lead</code>, <code>.display-*</code> — are for app UI: card titles, page section labels, dashboard headers. You control spacing. For article or CMS content where the typography owns its rhythm, jump to <a class="link" href="#prose">long-form content</a>.</p>
    <p>Single-property text utilities (<code>.fw-*</code>, <code>.fs-*</code>, <code>.text-*</code>, <code>.lh-*</code>) live with the rest of the text utilities, not on this page.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>Headings</h2>
    <p>Six levels rendered against the 14px baseline. Heading weight stays consistent across the scale; size carries the hierarchy.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div>
      <p class="h1">Heading one</p>
      <p class="h2">Heading two</p>
      <p class="h3">Heading three</p>
      <p class="h4">Heading four</p>
      <p class="h5">Heading five</p>
      <p class="h6">Heading six</p>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Reboot strips the default size and weight from <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>–<code>&lt;h6&gt;</code> so the heading element doesn&rsquo;t leak visual treatment into UI contexts (a card title that&rsquo;s an <code>&lt;h5&gt;</code> shouldn&rsquo;t pick up an extra 16px of margin). Use the matching class for the look; the element carries the document outline.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <p class="h3">A paragraph styled as an h3.</p>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Display</h2>
    <p>For hero titles and marketing pages. Lighter weight, tighter leading, sized larger than the regular heading scale.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div>
      <p class="display-1">Display 1</p>
      <p class="display-2">Display 2</p>
      <p class="display-3">Display 3</p>
      <p class="display-4">Display 4</p>
      <p class="display-5">Display 5</p>
      <p class="display-6">Display 6</p>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Lead</h2>
    <p>Add <code>.lead</code> to the first paragraph under a title for a slightly larger intro.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <div>
      <p class="h3">The cache layer</p>
      <p class="lead">A tiered cache backed by Redis with per-tenant eviction and a write-through fallback to Postgres for cold reads.</p>
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section id="prose">
    <h2>Long-form content</h2>
    <p>Wrap article or CMS content in <code>.prose</code>. It restores the reading typography that the foundation reboot strips &mdash; heading scale and rhythm, paragraph margins, list markers, blockquote treatment, inline code chip, tables, figure captions. Everything an article needs and nothing a dashboard does.</p>
    <p>The parent decides width. <code>.prose</code> is a typographic treatment, not a layout box.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <article style="max-width: 36rem;">
      <div class="prose">
        <p class="text-muted-foreground small">June 4, 2026 &middot; Engineering</p>
        <h2>Shipping a 14px baseline</h2>
        <p class="lead">Why we dropped the body text by 2 pixels and what changed downstream.</p>
        <p>The framework used to render body copy at <code>16px</code>, which is the common web default. That reads fine on a marketing page but feels heavy in a dashboard where every row counts. We took the baseline to <code>14px</code> and let the heading scale follow &mdash; without touching <code>html</code>, so <code>1rem</code> stays anchored at 16px and every component&rsquo;s rem-based math keeps its pixel meaning.</p>
        <h3>What moved</h3>
        <p>Every component that inherits from body shrank by about an eighth. That includes the default text in buttons, inputs, badges, and table cells. The grid stayed where it was, so column layouts kept their place.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Headings dropped proportionally, since the scale is hand-tuned for the 14px baseline.</li>
          <li>Form controls held their pixel heights through <code>height &times; density</code>, so dense forms kept their rhythm.</li>
          <li>Icons sized in <code>em</code> tracked the new baseline for free.</li>
        </ul>
        <blockquote>
          <p>The line you set as the baseline is the line every screen rounds to.</p>
        </blockquote>
        <h3>What stayed</h3>
        <p>Inter loads at 400, 500, 600, and 700. The display weights live on the same family, so a hero title and a body paragraph share their letterforms. Press <kbd>?</kbd> on any docs page to see the rest of the shortcuts.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
    {% endcall %}
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>Five variables retune <code>.prose</code> without touching component CSS. Override on <code>.prose</code> itself, or on any ancestor &mdash; the cascade scopes the change.</p>
    {% call ui.demo() %}
    <table style="width: 100%;">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align: start; padding-bottom: 0.5rem;">Variable</th>
          <th style="text-align: start; padding-bottom: 0.5rem;">Default</th>
          <th style="text-align: start; padding-bottom: 0.5rem;">Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;"><code>--st-prose-line-height</code></td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;">1.625</td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 0;">Reading leading</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;"><code>--st-prose-link-color</code></td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;">var(--st-primary)</td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 0;">Inline link color</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;"><code>--st-prose-marker-color</code></td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;">var(--st-muted-foreground)</td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 0;">List bullets / numbers</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;"><code>--st-prose-quote-border</code></td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;">var(--st-border)</td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 0;">Blockquote left rule</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;"><code>--st-prose-headings-color</code></td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 1rem 0.375rem 0;">var(--st-foreground)</td>
          <td style="padding: 0.375rem 0;">Heading color</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Components nested inside prose customize through the cascade. To enlarge <code>&lt;kbd&gt;</code> chips inside long-form content, set <code>--st-kbd-padding-y</code> on <code>.prose</code> &mdash; the kbd component reads its own variable and the cascade scopes the change. No prose-specific variable is invented for the nested component.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
